handle multiple consumers for a single REST API call to provide results as quickly as possible:
    you are likely looking for Parallel Request Aggregation (also known as the Scatter-Gather pattern).
    In this scenario, one "Orchestrator" receives the REST call, calls multiple downstream services (or data sources) at the same time, and combines the results.
1. The Strategy: Scatter-Gather (Parallelism)
    Instead of calling Service A, waiting, then calling Service B, you fire both requests simultaneously.
    Scatter: The API gateway or controller sends requests to multiple consumers/services.
    Gather: The controller waits for all responses to return, merges the data, and sends a single JSON response back to the user.
2. Implementation Options in Java
    A. CompletableFuture (Standard Java)
        This is the most common way to achieve parallel execution in a standard Spring Boot (MVC) app.
            public CompletableFuture<Response> handleRequest() {
                // Start both tasks in parallel
                CompletableFuture<User> user = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> userService.get());
                CompletableFuture<Order> orders = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> orderService.get());
            
                // Combine them when both are done
                return user.thenCombine(orders, (u, o) -> new Response(u, o));
            }
    B. Project Reactor (Spring WebFlux)
        If you want the highest performance with the least amount of memory, use WebFlux.
        It is designed specifically for this "non-blocking" parallel work.
        zip operator: It takes multiple publishers (Monos/Fluxes), waits for all of them to produce a value, and combines them.
            public Mono<Response> handleRequest() {
                Mono<User> userMono = userClient.fetchUser();
                Mono<Order> orderMono = orderClient.fetchOrders();
                return Mono.zip(userMono, orderMono)
                           .map(tuple -> new Response(tuple.getT1(), tuple.getT2()));
            }
3. Optimizing for "Quickest Result"
To truly get the result as fast as possible, implement these three "Parallel Performance" rules:
1. Fail-Fast (Timeouts)
    If you are calling 5 consumers and one is slow, your entire API call becomes slow.
    Action: Set a strict timeout (e.g., 500ms). If a consumer doesn't respond, return a partial result or an error immediately rather than making the user wait.
2. Virtual Threads (Java 21+)
    If you are on a modern Java version, use Virtual Threads. 
    They allow you to start thousands of "consumers" (threads) for parallel API calls without the massive memory overhead of traditional Platform Threads.
3. Hedged Requests
    If latency is your #1 priority, you can send the same request to two different instances of a consumer.
    Whichever one responds first is the one you use; you discard the second one. 
    This is expensive but ensures the lowest possible latency.

Method               Best For        Complexity    Performance
Sequential           Simple logic    Low            Slow
CompletableFuture    Standard Apps   Medium         Fast
WebFlux (zip)        High-scale APIs  High        Fastest (Non-blocking)
Virtual Threads      I/O Heavy tasks  Low        Very Fast

