Use a dedicated ThreadPool: Don't use the default ForkJoinPool for I/O tasks; create a custom Executor so your API calls don't starve other parts of the app.
Context Propagation: Remember that if you use Security (like JWT), you must manually pass the Security Context to the new parallel threads.
Error Handling: Use .exceptionally() or onErrorResume() to handle what happens if one consumer fails while others succeed.

How to avoid Duplicate messages at producer level:
    must address the "At Least Once" delivery guarantee that most messaging systems (like Kafka or Azure Service Bus) use by default.
    This usually happens when a producer sends a message, the broker receives it, but the ACK (acknowledgment) fails to reach the producer due to a network glitch.
    The producer then retries, causing a duplicate.
    Here is how you handle this in a modern Java ecosystem:

1. Enabling Idempotent Producers (Kafka)
In modern Kafka (0.11+), you can enable Idempotent Delivery. 
This ensures that even if a producer sends the same message multiple times, the broker only writes it to the log once.
Mechanism: The broker assigns a Producer ID (PID) and a Sequence Number to every message. 
        If the broker receives a sequence number it has already processed for that PID, it discards the duplicate.
    Java Configuration:
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ENABLE_IDEMPOTENCE_CONFIG, "true"); // The key setting
        props.put(ProducerConfig.ACKS_CONFIG, "all"); // Required for idempotence
        props.put(ProducerConfig.RETRIES_CONFIG, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

2. Application-Level Deduplication (The ID Pattern)
If your messaging system doesn't support native idempotence, 
    or if you want an extra layer of safety, you should implement a Unique Message ID.
    Generate a UUID: Assign a unique ID to every message before sending it.
    Database Check (Consumer Side): While this is technically handled at the consumer, 
                            the producer's job is to ensure the message_id is consistent across retries.
    Business Key: Instead of a random UUID, use a natural key (e.g., Order_ID + Status).

3. Transactional Outbox Pattern
    This is the "Gold Standard" for Java microservices. 
    Instead of sending a message directly to the broker, you save the message in your Local Database as part of the same ACID transaction as your business data.
        Step 1: Save the Order to the Orders table.
        Step 2: Save the OrderCreatedEvent to an Outbox table (same transaction).
        Step 3: A separate Message Relay (or a Debezium connector) reads from the Outbox table and publishes to the broker.
    This guarantees that a message is only produced if the database update was successful, and it provides a reliable record to prevent duplicates during retries.

4. Proper Exception Handling in Java
    When coding your producer, how you handle onCompletion or Future.get() determines if you create duplicates.
        producer.send(record, (metadata, exception) -> {
            if (exception != null) {
                // If the exception is 'Retriable', Kafka handles it.
                // If it's 'DuplicateSequenceException', you can safely ignore it 
                // because it means the broker already got the message!
                log.error("Send failed", exception);
            }
        });
5. Summary Table: Prevention Strategies
        Strategy                Complexity        Effectiveness        Best For
        Idempotent Producer     Low (Config only) High                 Kafka-based systems
        Message ID / UUID       Medium            High                 "Any broker (RabbitMQ, Service Bus)"
        Transactional Outbox    High              Maximum              Critical financial/data integrity
        Deduplication Store     Medium            Medium               High-volume streams

