1. Architectural Extensions
    As the system grows, you move away from simple synchronous calls to a more resilient, distributed architecture.
    CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation): Separate the "Write" logic from the "Read" logic.
            You could use a relational database for commands (Create/Update) and a NoSQL database like MongoDB or Elasticsearch for high-speed searches.
    Event-Driven Integration: Instead of just saving to a database, publish a ProductCreated or ProductPriceChanged event to Apache Kafka or Azure Service Bus.
                            This allows other services (like Inventory or Notifications) to react without direct coupling.
    API Gateway & Security: Introduce an API Gateway (like Spring Cloud Gateway) to handle cross-cutting concerns like rate limiting, logging,
                            and JWT authentication via OAuth2/OIDC.

2. Resilience and Performance
    Production systems must handle failures gracefully and respond quickly.
    Caching Layer: Implement Redis to store frequently accessed product data.
                    This reduces the load on your database for "Read" operations.
    Observability: Integrate Micrometer and Prometheus for metrics, and Zipkin or Jaeger for distributed tracing.
                    This is crucial when your product service starts talking to other microservices via Feign.
    Bulkheading & Circuit Breaking: Use Resilience4j to wrap your external calls. 
                        If a downstream service is slow, the circuit breaker prevents your Product service from hanging.

3. Database Maturity
    Simple JPA works for basics, but scaling requires more control.
    Database Migrations: Use Flyway or Liquibase. Never let Hibernate auto-generate your production schema (ddl-auto=update is dangerous).
                        Version-controlled scripts ensure your AKS environments stay in sync.
    Soft Deletes: Instead of repository.delete(), add an is_deleted boolean flag. 
                    This preserves data history and makes "undoing" an accidental deletion possible.
    Auditing: Use Spring Data JPA's @CreatedDate and @LastModifiedBy to automatically track who changed a product and when.

