Optimistic vs persimitic lock:

1. Pessimistic Locking
    Pessimistic locking assumes the "worst-case scenario"—that a collision will happen.
    It prevents conflicts by locking the record the moment it is read, ensuring no one else can touch it until the transaction is finished.
    How it works: When a thread reads data, it places an exclusive lock on the row (e.g., SELECT ... FOR UPDATE in SQL).
    Behavior: Other threads attempting to read or write that same row must wait (block) until the first thread commits or rolls back.
    Best for:
        High-contention environments (many updates on the same row).
        Operations where the cost of a collision is extremely high (e.g., banking transactions, inventory stock reduction).

    public interface ProductRepository extends JpaRepository<Product, Long> {
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    Optional<Product> findById(Long id);
    }

2. Optimistic Locking
    Optimistic locking assumes the "best-case scenario"—that collisions are rare. It does not lock the row during the read. 
    Instead, it checks for changes only at the moment of the update.
    How it works: It typically uses a Version Column or a Timestamp.
        Thread A reads the record (Version 1).
        Thread B reads the record (Version 1).
        Thread A updates the record and increments it to Version 2.
        Thread B tries to update, but the database sees the current version is 2 while Thread B still thinks it's 1. 
        The update fails, throwing an OptimisticLockException.
    Behavior: No blocking occurs. Threads work in parallel, but one might fail and need to retry.
    Best for:
        Low-contention environments.
        Distributed systems/Microservices (where holding a database connection open for a long time is expensive).
        Applications with high "Read-to-Write" ratios.

        @Entity
        public class Product {
            @Id
            private Long id;
            
            @Version
            private Integer version; // Incrementing counter
        }

| **Feature**      | **Pessimistic Locking**           | **Optimistic Locking**                                    |
| ---------------- | --------------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Approach**     | Block upfront                     | Validate at the end                                       |
| **Concurrency**  | Low (threads wait in line)        | High (threads run freely)                                 |
| **Performance**  | Slower due to locking overhead    | Faster (unless many retries occur)                        |
| **Deadlocks**    | Possible if not handled carefully | Not possible                                              |
| **Typical Tool** | `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`           | `@Version` annotation in Hibernate / Java Persistence API |


rerouting mechism in apache camel between different service and shadow logic implemntation:

1. Rerouting Mechanisms in Camel
Rerouting is the process of dynamically deciding where a message should go based on content, headers, or external state.
Content-Based Router (Choice): The most common mechanism. It acts like a switch statement, routing messages based on predicates.
    from("direct:start")
        .choice()
            .when(header("serviceType").isEqualTo("inventory"))
                .to("http://inventory-service/api")
            .when(header("serviceType").isEqualTo("shipping"))
                .to("http://shipping-service/api")
            .otherwise()
                .to("log:unknown-service")
        .end();
Dynamic Router: Unlike a static choice, a Dynamic Router evaluates a rule at runtime to determine the next destination. 
                It keeps calling a bean until the bean returns null, indicating the route is finished.

Recipient List: Used when a message needs to be sent to a list of endpoints calculated at runtime.
Tip: In 2026, many teams use this to broadcast events to a list of subscribers stored in a Redis cache.

Shadow Logic (Traffic Shadowing)
Shadow Logic involves sending a copy of production traffic to a new "shadow" service to test its performance and accuracy without affecting the actual user response.
To achieve this in Camel, you use the Wire Tap EIP.
The Wire Tap is a fixed recipient list that sends a copy of the exchange to a secondary destination in a separate thread.

Implementation Example:
    from("direct:production-inbound")
        // 1. Shadow Logic: Tap the traffic and send a copy to the experimental service
        .wireTap("direct:shadow-service")
            .copy(true) // Ensure a deep copy of the message is made
            .executorService(myCustomThreadPool) // Run shadow logic in a background pool
        .end()
        
        // 2. Real Logic: Continue the main production flow immediately
        .to("http://production-service/api");
    
    from("direct:shadow-service")
        .log("Processing shadow traffic for testing...")
        .to("http://beta-service/api");

Class-Level Logging:
    Logging allows you to see what is happening inside your code at runtime. Class-level logging is the most common approach.
    Implementation: Usually done via SLF4J with Logback or Log4j2.
    Hierarchy: You can set different "Log Levels" for different packages.
        com.myapp.service -> Set to DEBUG (very verbose).
        com.myapp.security -> Set to INFO (only major events).
            
            public class UserService {
                // This is class-level logging
                private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(UserService.class);
            
                public void processRequest(String dynamicId) {
                    logger.info("Processing request for ID: {}", dynamicId);
                }
            }
